                    "company": "KU Leuven",
                    "description": "The Antwerp 'Consuetudines compilatae' is one of the few examples of statutory legislation in early modern Europe that contains regulations on commercial partnerships. As a postdoctoral researcher, I studied the nature and origin of this Antwerp company law and compared it with its medieval and early modern European counterparts. I showed that Italian examples of statutory legislation did exert a substantive influence on Antwerp company law, but that such influence was not unconditional nor exclusive. The reception of Italian examples always occurred with respect for local usages. In addition, one can observe genuine influences of French legislation, medieval doctrine, Roman law, and material legal sources like equity and reason. In this way, I demonstrated the unique nature of Antwerp customary company law.\nHowever, since statutory legislation merely represents the desires of local authorities, they are not necessarily in accordance with historical reality. Thus, I studied the corporate practices that were actually applied by the Antwerp merchants around 1600. By means of an in-depth analysis of the Antwerp notarial archives, I first demonstrated that the influence of the aforementioned foreign examples was not always entirely innovative. Secondly, I gave ample proof of the discrepancy between some of the city\u2019s statutory regulations on commercial partnerships and the much more diverse and complex commercial reality.",
                    "title": "Postdoctoral researcher",
                    "employment_type": null
                }
            ]
        },
