                    "company": "Maastricht University",
                    "description": "On 7 October 1531, the Emperor Charles V issued an ordinance prescribing the recording of all customs in use in the Habsburg Netherlands. In my doctoral dissertation I offered an insight into the internal development of the recording process, which has long remained in the shadow of its external history. On the basis of an in-depth analysis of two compilations, the Antwerp 'Consuetudines compilatae' (1608) and the 'Guelders Country and Town Statute Book' (1620), I revealed a number of factors which had a decisive impact on the form and content of early modern compilations of customary law.\nAt first, I unravelled the myth of unadulterated custom, since both compilations appeared to be a mere patchwork of various material and formal legal sources, all too often alien to local custom. Secondly, I provided a first description of the phenomenon of \u2018customary acculturation\u2019, whereby the recording process of the customs of one specific town is based on the compilation of another. In this connection, the Antwerp-Roermond case shows that one compilation may dramatically affect both form and content of another. Thirdly, such a normative assimilation went hand in hand with a structural assimilation, whereby the application of humanist ordering principles played an important role. The effect of legal humanism can also be observed in the emancipatory process with regard to content. The 'auctoritas' of Roman law is in decline, and \u2018best law\u2019 becomes the new standard, irrespective of its origin.",
                    "title": "PhD student - Legal History",
                    "employment_type": null
                }
            ]
